            AppRoutes = """["/quality"]""",
            Tags = """["quality","qc","inspection","quiz"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"passingScore":80,"questionsPerQuiz":8,"shuffleOptions":true,"showExplanationsAfterSubmit":true,"questions":[{"id":"qc1","text":"You need to inspect incoming material for a specific part that has a standard checklist. What is the most efficient workflow?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Go to Quality → Inspections tab, click New Inspection, select the QC template for that part, enter the lot number, and work through the pre-populated checklist items","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"Create a new QC template from scratch each time you perform an inspection"},{"id":"c","text":"Go to the Parts module and record inspection results in the part notes field"},{"id":"d","text":"Skip the inspection and mark the lot as accepted in Inventory"}],"explanation":"QC templates define reusable checklists. When creating an inspection, selecting a template pre-populates all the checklist items. Enter the lot number for traceability, and record pass/fail results for each check."},{"id":"qc2","text":"An inspection has a results summary showing '4/6'. What does this mean?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"4 out of 6 inspectors approved the part"},{"id":"b","text":"4 out of 6 individual checklist checks passed","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The part scored 4 out of 6 on a quality rating scale"},{"id":"d","text":"4 of 6 lots in the batch were inspected"}],"explanation":"The results summary shows how many individual checklist items passed out of the total. '4/6' means 4 checks passed and 2 failed. This gives a quick at-a-glance view of inspection quality."},{"id":"qc3","text":"A customer reports a defect in parts from lot L-2024-0042. You need to find every job, PO, and bin location that used material from this lot. Where do you look?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Quality → Lots tab → search for L-2024-0042 → click the traceability button (tree icon) to see all linked jobs, production runs, POs, bin locations, and inspections","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"Run a report in the Reports module filtered by lot number"},{"id":"c","text":"Check the Inventory module for bin contents matching that lot"},{"id":"d","text":"Search for the lot number in the Kanban board search"}],"explanation":"The Lot Tracking tab has a traceability button per row (tree icon) that opens a dialog showing every linked record: jobs, production runs, purchase orders, bin locations, and QC inspections. This is the fastest way to trace a lot through your operation."},{"id":"qc4","text":"You are monitoring a critical dimension on a CNC-machined part and notice the SPC chart shows a point beyond the upper control limit (UCL). What should you expect from the system?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Nothing — the chart is informational only and does not trigger any alerts"},{"id":"b","text":"An out-of-control (OOC) event is automatically generated in the OOC Events tab, with severity based on the rule violated. If the characteristic has 'Notify on OOC' enabled, a notification is also sent.","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The system automatically stops the CNC machine on the shop floor"},{"id":"d","text":"The part status is automatically changed to Obsolete"}],"explanation":"When SPC detects an out-of-control condition (like a point beyond 3-sigma), it creates an OOC event with the appropriate severity. If the characteristic has 'Notify on OOC' enabled, relevant personnel receive a notification. The OOC event can then be acknowledged and a CAPA created if needed."},{"id":"qc5","text":"A batch of supplier-provided material fails incoming inspection. You document this as an NCR. What NCR type and detection stage should you select?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Type: Internal, Detection Stage: In Process"},{"id":"b","text":"Type: Customer, Detection Stage: Receiving"},{"id":"c","text":"Type: Supplier, Detection Stage: Receiving","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"Type: Supplier, Detection Stage: Final Inspection"}],"explanation":"Since the defect is in supplier-provided material, the NCR type is 'Supplier'. Since it was caught during incoming material inspection, the detection stage is 'Receiving'. This combination accurately categorizes the non-conformance for reporting and vendor quality tracking."},{"id":"qc6","text":"An NCR has been investigated and the quality team decides the non-conforming parts can be reworked to meet specification. What is the correct disposition code?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Use As Is"},{"id":"b","text":"Rework","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Sort & Screen"},{"id":"d","text":"Concession"}],"explanation":"'Rework' means the non-conforming material will be repaired or reworked to bring it into conformance with the specification. 'Use As Is' would accept it without changes, 'Sort & Screen' would separate good from bad, and 'Concession' would require customer approval."},{"id":"qc7","text":"A recurring quality issue has been identified through multiple NCRs. You need to perform a root cause analysis and track corrective actions to closure. Which feature should you use?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Create an ECO to document the engineering change"},{"id":"b","text":"Create a CAPA with type Corrective, link it to the NCRs, perform root cause analysis (e.g., 5 Whys or Fishbone), document corrective actions, and track through verification and effectiveness check","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Add notes to each NCR describing the corrective action taken"},{"id":"d","text":"Create a job on the Kanban board to track the fix"}],"explanation":"CAPAs are designed for systematic problem resolution. Create a Corrective CAPA from the source (here, NCR), then advance it one phase at a time with the forward-arrow action: Open → Root Cause Analysis → Action Planning → Implementation → Verification → Effectiveness Check → Closed. The root-cause method (5 Whys, Fishbone, Fault Tree, 8D, Pareto, Is/Is-Not) and write-up are phase work done after the CAPA is opened — they are not part of the create dialog, which captures type, source, title, descriptions, owner, priority, and due date."},{"id":"qc8","text":"A design change to a part requires updating the BOM, revising the drawing, and modifying the CNC program. Which Quality feature manages this controlled change?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Create an NCR to document the required changes"},{"id":"b","text":"Create an ECO with change type 'Revision', list the affected items (part, BOM, operations) with old and new values, and advance through Draft → Review → Approved → Implementation → Implemented","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Update the part record directly in the Parts module"},{"id":"d","text":"Create a CAPA to track the design change"}],"explanation":"Engineering Change Orders (ECOs) manage controlled changes to parts, processes, and documentation. Create an ECO with the appropriate change type, list all affected items with their old and new values, get approval through the review process, and track implementation status."},{"id":"qc9","text":"A digital caliper needs its annual calibration. How do you manage this in the Quality module?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Go to Quality → Gages tab, find the caliper, click it to open the detail, then click 'Record Calibration' and enter the date, result, lab name, standards used, and as-found/as-left conditions","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"Update the caliper's status to 'In Service' and change the last calibration date manually"},{"id":"c","text":"Create a maintenance work order in the Assets module"},{"id":"d","text":"Record the calibration as a time entry in Time Tracking"}],"explanation":"The Gages tab provides a complete calibration management workflow. Open the gage detail, record a new calibration with the result (Pass/Fail/Adjusted/Out of Tolerance), lab name, certificate, standards used, and as-found/as-left conditions. The system automatically updates the next calibration due date."},{"id":"qc10","text":"You scan a barcode while on the Quality page's Lots tab. What happens?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Nothing — the scanner is not active on the Quality page"},{"id":"b","text":"The scanned value fills the lot search field, letting you quickly find the scanned lot","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"A new inspection is automatically created for the scanned lot"},{"id":"d","text":"The system opens the traceability dialog for the scanned lot"}],"explanation":"The Quality page sets the scanner context to 'quality'. On the Lots tab, a barcode scan fills the lot search field with the scanned value. On the Inspections tab, it fills the inspection search field instead. This enables quick lookups on the shop floor."},{"id":"qc11","text":"What is the difference between control limits (UCL/LCL) and spec limits (USL/LSL) on an SPC chart?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"They are the same thing — just different naming conventions"},{"id":"b","text":"Control limits are calculated from actual process data and show natural variation boundaries. Spec limits are defined by engineering requirements and show the acceptable range for the product.","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Control limits are set by management, spec limits are set by customers"},{"id":"d","text":"Spec limits are always wider than control limits"}],"explanation":"Control limits (UCL/LCL) are statistically calculated from measurement data — they show the expected range of natural process variation (typically +/- 3 sigma from the mean). Spec limits (USL/LSL) are engineering requirements defined on the SPC characteristic — they define what the customer or design requires. A process can be in control (within UCL/LCL) but still out of spec, or vice versa."},{"id":"qc12","text":"A new operator opens the New Inspection dialog and asks where to build the part's checklist and tick off each check as pass or fail. What should you tell them?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The New Inspection dialog only captures Template, Job ID, Lot Number, and Notes. You pick an existing predefined template from the dropdown; the Quality page has no visual template builder, and there is no place to tick off each check pass or fail yet — it creates and tracks inspections rather than scoring each check.","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"Click 'Add Checklist Item' inside the dialog to build the checklist on the fly, then toggle each item pass or fail before saving"},{"id":"c","text":"Switch the dialog to Builder mode to author the template, then to Results mode to record each measurement"},{"id":"d","text":"Templates and results are both entered in the Notes field as free text"}],"explanation":"The Quality page is for creating and tracking inspections. QC templates are set up ahead of time for your site by an administrator and are selected from a dropdown when creating an inspection — there is no template builder on the page. The dialog captures only Template, Job ID, Lot Number, and Notes, and the inspection is created In Progress. Recording pass/fail outcomes for each individual check is not yet available on this page."}]}"""
