        // ── Advanced Reference ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Quality — Advanced Reference",
            Slug = "quality-reference",
            Summary = "Deeper how-to for experienced quality staff: when to recalculate control limits, how to read Cp/Cpk/Pp/Ppk, setting CAPA priority, choosing the right NCR disposition, and managing gage calibration.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Reference,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/quality"]""",
            Tags = """["quality","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Recalculating Control Limits — When and How\n\nControl limits are not the same as spec limits, and you never type them in by hand. They are calculated from the readings you have already recorded — the process tells you its own natural spread. On the SPC Charts tab, when you have gathered a solid baseline, use Recalculate Limits to set fresh UCL, LCL, and center line from that data.\n\nDo it when:\n\n- You are first setting up a characteristic and finally have enough subgroups to trust. You need at least two subgroups before the tool will compute anything, and honestly you want 20-25 for a stable baseline.\n- The process has genuinely changed for the better — a new fixture, a re-ground tool, a corrected setup. Old limits describe the old process; recalculate so the chart reflects reality.\n\nDo NOT recalculate just because a point went out of control. That point is the chart doing its job. Recalculating to \"make it fit\" hides the very signal you set the chart up to catch.\n\nGood practice: recalculate from a known-good window. If the first week was a mess and the process settled after that, scope the baseline to the good stretch so the limits describe a stable process, not the shakedown. The tool keeps your old limit sets on file, so every recalculation is traceable — you can always show an auditor which data a given set of limits came from and when. Only the current set drives the live chart and the out-of-control flags.\n\nUnder the hood the tool uses the standard SPC constants (the A2, D3, D4, d2 factors from any control-chart table) for your subgroup size, so an X-bar and R chart built here matches what you would get by hand. For subgroups of ten or more it switches to an S chart, which estimates spread more accurately at larger sample sizes.\n\n## Reading Cp, Cpk, Pp, and Ppk\n\nThese four capability numbers answer one question: does the part's tolerance have enough room for the spread your process actually produces? The tool figures them out for you — here is how to read them.\n\n- **Cp** — potential capability. How the tolerance compares to the process spread if the process were perfectly centered. It ignores where the process is actually running, so a high Cp with junk parts means you are running off-center.\n- **Cpk** — actual capability. Same idea, but it accounts for centering, so it is always the honest number of the pair. Watch Cpk, not Cp.\n- **Pp / Ppk** — the same two ideas measured over the long haul, using every reading rather than the tight within-subgroup spread. Cpk is your short-term \"how good can this run be,\" Ppk is \"how good has it actually been over time.\" When Ppk sits well below Cpk, something is drifting between runs — tool wear, shift-to-shift differences, material lots.\n\nCommon targets: Cpk of 1.33 is the usual bar for \"capable,\" and 1.67 for safety-critical or customer-flagged characteristics. Below 1.0, the process spread is wider than the tolerance — you are making bad parts even when nothing looks wrong, and 100% inspection or a process fix is the only safety net. The tool never blocks you on a low number; it just shows it. Acting on it is your call, and a low Cpk is your early warning long before a part actually goes out of spec. Remember these compare against the spec limits (USL/LSL) from engineering, which are a different thing from the control limits the chart calculates.\n\n## Setting CAPA Priority and Knowing Where It Came From\n\nWhen you open a CAPA you set a priority from 1 to 5: 1 = Critical, 2 = High, 3 = Medium (the default), 4 = Low, 5 = Informational. Use it honestly — a safety or customer-escape issue is a 1 and should jump the queue; a nice-to-have process tidy-up is a 4 or 5. The priority is what sorts the list and tells your team what to grab next, so resist the urge to mark everything Critical.\n\nEvery CAPA also records where it came from: an NCR, a customer complaint, an internal or external audit, an SPC out-of-control event, a management review, or Other. This source matters at audit time — a registrar wants to see that findings actually turn into CAPAs, and the source is the thread that proves it. When you launch a CAPA straight from an out-of-control event or an NCR, that link is captured for you, so the CAPA points back to exactly what triggered it.\n\nThe create dialog is deliberately short — type, source, title, problem, owner, priority, due date. The real substance comes later. The root-cause method (5 Whys, Fishbone, Fault Tree, 8D, Pareto, Is/Is-Not), the analysis write-up, the action tasks, and the effectiveness-check date all belong to the phases you work through after the CAPA is open, not to the moment you create it.\n\n## The Six NCR Dispositions — Choosing the Right One\n\nDisposition is the decision about what physically happens to the non-conforming material. You set it when the NCR reaches the Dispositioned stage, and it does not change the affected or defective counts you already recorded — those stay as the record of what was found.\n\n- **Use As Is** — the material is out of spec but fit for purpose. Accept it as-is, no rework. Use sparingly and document why it is acceptable.\n- **Rework** — repair or re-machine the parts back into spec, then re-inspect. The most common disposition when the defect is fixable.\n- **Scrap** — the parts cannot be saved. Discard them and record the loss.\n- **Return to Vendor** — defective incoming material goes back to the supplier. Pair this with a Supplier-type NCR so it feeds vendor quality tracking.\n- **Sort & Screen** — you do not trust the whole lot, so 100% inspect it and pull the bad units out. Common when a defect rate is unknown.\n- **Concession** — accept the non-conforming material, but only with the customer's documented sign-off or an approved deviation. This is the one disposition that reaches outside your walls, so never use it without that paper trail.\n\nThe practical split: Use As Is and Concession accept the parts (one on your judgment, one on the customer's), Rework saves them, Sort & Screen separates them, and Scrap and Return to Vendor get rid of them.\n\n## What Happens When You Record a Calibration\n\nRecording a calibration on a gage does more than log the date — it resets the whole calibration clock for that instrument, so you rarely have to touch the schedule by hand.\n\n- The next-due date is set automatically from the calibration date plus the gage's interval. Calibrate a yearly gage today and it is scheduled a year out; the same date lands on both the calibration record and the gage itself, and the last-calibrated date updates too.\n- The gage's status follows the result. A Fail flips the gage to Out of Service — it is out of tolerance and must not be used until repaired or replaced. Any other result (Pass, Adjusted, Out of Tolerance-but-corrected) puts it back In Service. Either way the interval clock restarts from the calibration date.\n- The person who recorded the calibration is captured automatically, so the sign-off is on the record without you typing your name.\n\nTo stay ahead of the schedule, use the due-soon view — it lists every active gage coming due within a window you choose (30 days by default), soonest first. This is the calibration coordinator's Monday-morning list: pull it, see what is coming up, and get gages to the lab before they lapse. A gage that is past due should not be measuring parts — treat a lapsed calibration like an out-of-tolerance one until it is re-certified.\n\n## Keeping the Gage-to-Measurement Chain Traceable\n\nOne habit ties this whole tab together and it is the one auditors probe hardest: link the gage to the measurement. When you set up an SPC characteristic, point it at the specific gage used to measure it. When a certificate arrives from the calibration lab, attach the PDF and note the traceable standards used to the calibration record. Done consistently, this gives you an unbroken chain — this reading was taken with this gage, which was in calibration on that date, traceable back to a national standard. That chain is what turns a folder of measurements into defensible quality data, and it is exactly what a customer audit or an ISO/AS9100 assessor asks you to walk them through.","sections":[]}"""
        });

